Jasperw: it's to avoid fragmentation too<nl>if the disk is that full  there's no space left to apply a good block layout policy<nl>chain-lightning: it's not really needed<nl>Jasperw: I think it'll work if it is mounted read-only  but you'd have to reboot after<nl>ruelle: and you should NOT change that limit. it is there for a reason BTW.<nl>Jasperw: do you know how FFS works internally?<nl>yeah  but looking at his df output  it's not huge.<nl>Jasperw: FFS *needs* free space or it'll fragment heavily. if the FS is huge and has lots of activity  then it'll need a lot of free space...<nl>Jasperw: FFS tries to spread unrelated data in multiple cylinder groups and keep related data in nearer cylinder groups (based on which file owns the block and common parent directory)  occasionally spreading related data when large sequential chunks have been layout nearly. if there is not enough free space to make this work  then you lose. it WILL fragment like shit.<nl>ruelle: you don't use defrags with FFS or FFS-derived FS (like ext2fs). these FSes try to avoid fragmentation in the first place.<nl>ruelle: prolly because running windows gives it quite a beating<nl>ruelle: yeah.. but I don't think this in particular affects fragmentation...<nl>chain-lightning: well  that's still pretty light activity. it shouldn't affect fragmentation level of the whole FS...<nl>

That can set the initial bias for any heuristics when the UA is trying to decide how to present the image to the user<nl>(The heuristics might be as simple as <nl>I haven't looked at any relevant statistics from current content so I don't really know :-)<nl>(Or the heuristics might be some futuristic image analysis thing with a Bayesian classifier or whatever it is)<nl>If you count the spacer and background images in http://canvex.lazyilluminati.com/misc/imgs.xhtml then there's quite a lot of decorative ones<nl>but it'd be easy for a UA to just ignore all files called spacer.gif<nl>&<nl>They're both problems  but it seems easier to solve the first problem (by identifying intentionally-omitted-alt with some new syntax  so authors can make sure their critical images don't get ignored by incorrect heuristics) than the second problem  and partially solving one problem is usually better than solving none (except when solving that problem takes far too much effort to be worthwhile and distracts from other problems :-) )<nl>

JAWS and other screen readers provide means of navigating to data tables by means of a quick navigation keystroke. The table summary or caption  whichever is present  are then spoken automatically  giving immediate context to what the data table is about.<nl>b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: I encounter them mostly on pages which try to adhere to WCAG  which also have mostly navigation items in lists  proper heading markup etc.<nl>b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: JAWS indicates if it's a summary  the caption is spoken without extra indication.
